    "side_effects_description": "The possible side effects of using Polystichum oculatum improperly include experiencing nausea, which can be caused by its toxic compounds such as polystichic acids and furostanol saponins. These compounds can also lead to vomiting, making it essential to use the plant with caution. Developing diarrhea is another potential side effect, which may be attributed to the plant's ability to induce gastrointestinal irritation. Furthermore, experiencing vomiting can be a symptom of Polystichum oculatum's toxic properties, which can be exacerbated by improper use. These side effects can be severe and are often associated with the plant's misuse, highlighting the importance of proper handling and administration.",
    "uses": "Polystichum oculatum has been traditionally used in folk medicine in various parts of the world, particularly in East Asia. Its leaves are said to have anti-inflammatory properties and are used to treat various health issues. In traditional Chinese medicine, the plant is believed to have a cooling effect and is used to treat fever and other heat-related conditions. The plant's leaves are also used to treat digestive problems, such as diarrhea and stomach pain. Further research is needed to confirm the plant's medicinal properties and potential health benefits.",
    "taxonomy": "Polystichum oculatum is a species of fern in the family Dryopteridaceae. It is native to the Pacific Northwest region of North America. The classification of this plant includes its kingdom as Plantae, and its phylum as Pteridophyta. It belongs to the class Polypodiopsida and the order Polypodiales. This species is also known as the spotted shield fern due to its distinctive appearance.",
    "benefits": "Polystichum oculatum, a species of fern native to Japan, is rich in antioxidants and has been traditionally used in herbal medicine. It is believed to have anti-inflammatory properties, which can help to reduce swelling and ease pain. The plant is also thought to have antimicrobial and antifungal properties, making it useful in treating various infections. Additionally, Polystichum oculatum may help to boost the immune system, protecting the body against diseases. However, further research is needed to confirm the effectiveness of these potential health benefits.",
    "parts": "Polystichum oculatum, a type of evergreen fern native to East Asia, has been used in traditional medicine for various purposes. The medicinal parts of this plant are primarily its fronds and rhizomes. The fronds are used to treat respiratory issues, such as coughs and bronchitis, while the rhizomes are used for their anti-inflammatory properties. The rhizomes are also believed to have a laxative effect. In traditional medicine, Polystichum oculatum is often used to treat digestive issues and promote overall health.",
    "intro": "Polystichum oculatum, also known as the spiny wood fern, is a type of perennial fern native to Japan and parts of East Asia. This plant is valued for its potential health benefits, which include anti-inflammatory, antioxidant, and antimicrobial properties, making it useful in traditional medicine for treating various ailments. The bioactive constituents of Polystichum oculatum include flavonoids, phenolic acids, and terpenoids, which contribute to its medicinal properties. In traditional herbal medicine, Polystichum oculatum is often used to prepare teas, infusions, and tinctures to treat conditions such as fever, respiratory infections, and digestive issues."
